{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-a66b6aceb507fd73", "type": "tool_result", "content": "# Neural networks for Text-to-Speech evaluation\narXiv: 2604.08562\nAuthors: Ilya Trofimenko, David Kocharyan, Aleksandr Zaitsev, Pavel Repnikov, Mark Levin, Nikita Shevtsov\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_other\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of a collaborative-filtering-inspired data standardization method (Std SOMOS) that mitigates rater bias and consistently improves absolute MOS prediction accuracy.\n  2. Development of NeuralSBS, a HuBERT-backed model with antisymmetric bilinear pooling that achieves 73.7% accuracy for relative side-by-side TTS evaluation.\n  3. Optimization of the MOSNet architecture through custom sequence-length batching, padding masking, and sequence-level MSE loss to stabilize training and reduce prediction error.\n  4. Proposal of WhisperBert, a multimodal stacking ensemble combining Whisper audio features and BERT text embeddings via weak learners, which achieves an RMSE of ~0.40, significantly outperforming the human inter-rater baseline.\n  5. Demonstration that naive multimodal fusion via cross-attention degrades performance, whereas late-stage ensemble stacking effectively leverages both audio and text modalities.\n  6. Reporting of negative results for SpeechLM-based architectures and zero-shot LLM evaluators, highlighting the necessity of dedicated metric learning frameworks over general-purpose models.\n\nTags: Eval, Eval/学习, TTS", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "43cc25bf-5eba-44be-8383-be92c2121c69", "uuid": "e3e18345-4664-4250-9d99-a9b2dd060c24", "timestamp": "2026-07-12T09:19:52.672Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "# Neural networks for Text-to-Speech evaluation\narXiv: 2604.08562\nAuthors: Ilya Trofimenko, David Kocharyan, Aleksandr Zaitsev, Pavel Repnikov, Mark Levin, Nikita Shevtsov\nYear: 2026 | Venue: \nTopic: speech_other\nStatus: unread\n\nContributions:\n  1. Introduction of a collaborative-filtering-inspired data standardization method (Std SOMOS) that mitigates rater bias and consistently improves absolute MOS prediction accuracy.\n  2. Development of NeuralSBS, a HuBERT-backed model with antisymmetric bilinear pooling that achieves 73.7% accuracy for relative side-by-side TTS evaluation.\n  3. Optimization of the MOSNet architecture through custom sequence-length batching, padding masking, and sequence-level MSE loss to stabilize training and reduce prediction error.\n  4. Proposal of WhisperBert, a multimodal stacking ensemble combining Whisper audio features and BERT text embeddings via weak learners, which achieves an RMSE of ~0.40, significantly outperforming the human inter-rater baseline.\n  5. Demonstration that naive multimodal fusion via cross-attention degrades performance, whereas late-stage ensemble stacking effectively leverages both audio and text modalities.\n  6. Reporting of negative results for SpeechLM-based architectures and zero-shot LLM evaluators, highlighting the necessity of dedicated metric learning frameworks over general-purpose models.\n\nTags: Eval, Eval/学习, TTS", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
